is a world of difference if a woman kills her husband in a moment of rage over his infidelity, or if she coldly calculates his murder just to cash in a huge insurance policy and run off with the cabana boy. As Rusty pointed out, the law has always recognized this by categorizing murder based on <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>intent</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->. By making hate crime legislation, we are recognizing that hate is a very bad sort of intent - right up there with insurance gain.<br>
<br>
There is a difference between assault and robbery to support a drug habit, and assault and robbery to punish someone for their sexual identity. I think when a person is targeted for crime based on race, sexual orientation or religion it is far more heinous than if it is based on the perpetrator's drug addiction - even if the end result is identical. If some drunk asshole starts a little bonfire in my yard, that's bad, but if the bonfire is a burning cross started by an anti-abortionist, that's far worse IMHO.<br>
<br>
Hate crime creates a base level of fear for those in the target group. We ALL probably live with some level of fear/anxiety about getting attacked by a mugger or rapist, but if you are gay/Jewish/black or whatever, then you also may have to live with fear/anxiety about being attacked for your identity alone. It's unfair that anyone should be in a greater degree of danger based on their identity, and hate crime legislation tries to ameliorate that.<br>
<br>
The problem with hate crime legislation is that motivation can be hard to prove. If a xian and a jew argue in a bar and get in a fight, where they might have previously been charged with disorderly conduct or assault, one of them may now be faced with much harsher &quot;hate crime&quot; charges even though he didn't know the other's religion. Lawyers are going to leverage this legislation like crazy and that is the real problem that I see with it.<br>
<br>
DL<br>
<br>
