<br>
The problem with Hate Crime Legislation is that it sucks.  It is too vague and ambiguous and worst of all applied inequitably.  Example: A racist black kills a white, they will not be sentenced under hate crime law.  A white who is NOT racist kills someone and they happen to be black, they will be sentenced.  Every time. It is too volitile a political issue not to be subrogated by it.  DA's need to appear diligent in their prosections, but they don't want to appear racist either.<br>
<br>
Federal sentencing standards are rigidly controlled to generate equitable punishments.  They have a grid and an evaluation chart for totaling a score to determine the range the criminal falls within.  Statistics are kept and a &quot;Hanging Judge&quot; will be shuffled around out of damaging roles by assignment committees.  State sentencing is far more liberal with its applications.  It is not required to be reported and judges have far greater discretion in application.  Even so, in CT at least there is a sentencing review commission and if a criminal feels they were dealt with unfairly, they can file a complaint.<br>
<br>
Crimes are covered under the law.  Hate crimes are heinous in nature.  Heinous crimes are covered.  A new categorization does not need to be created simple so some legislators can book brownie points with their constituents for re-election.<br>
