<br>
How accurate are these statistics if hate crime legislation hasn't actually passed?  These people were charged with crimes in general, and they haven't stood in a court of law to be charged specifically with hate crimes.  I'm sure that many of these convictions fit in with the definition of hate crimes, but it hasn't been determined exactly how many.  Also, what was the racial background of the victim in all 2,253 cases where a black was convicted?  Followers of people such as Farakhan commit crimes against Jews because he convinced many of them that Jews are at the root of all their suffering.  How many of them committed crimes against gays?<br>
<br>
&quot;!5 out of 20 death role convictions have been against a non white . This statistic alone suggest we do not apply our laws in a fair manner.&quot;<br>
<br>
This should be irrelevant when it comes to determine if hate crime legislation should pass.  We can't all of a sudden punish white people because some non-whites got screwed.  We need to focus on fixing the system to make sure that people in poor socio-economic conditions get fair representation in a court of law.  Throwing more white people in jail doesn't change the suffering of a black man who is sitting in jail because he was wrongly accused.  The statistics will also be skewed because of those poor socio-economic conditions.  It is no secret that kids who grow up in poverty have higher rates of criminal activity and drug use.  If a high percentage of blacks and hispanics live in these impovershed conditions, then they naturally will commit a high percentage of the crimes, and therefore they will make up a high percentage of the prison population.  I'm not saying that people of a certain race are inherently prone to crime, so I hope nobody is taking what I say out of context.  I am saying that certain living conditions breed more crime, and unfortunately many minorities live in these poor conditions.  I think improving conditions can help curb the crime rate among these groups, but if they do commit the crime, then they need to do the time.  I don't want a murderer released because our statistics need to look more &quot;fair&quot;.  <br>
<br>
