erything to do with scoring political points for the elected officials. Just like Dubyah's late term abortion laws, which already had existing statues covering exactly the same scenario. This type of unnecessary, redundant legislation only makes application of the law more difficult and unwieldy.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Hate crimes isn't about white and black nor black and white. Since 9/11 most of the hate crimes have been against moslems. Somehow this thread has narrowed it down to black versus white.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->As I said when I made the comparison, it was an arbitrary selection, I could have said 'crimes against the french' just as easily.  We have not narrowed anything, we have simply chosen an easy and well worn example.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Mens Rhea</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> defines a criminal's intent in prosecution. The act itself, or <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Actus Rheus</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, defines the crime they have committed. <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Aggravating factors</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, if they are convicted of the crime, increase the severity of their sentencing. <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Mitigating factors</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> decrease it. Crimes of a heinous nature, unprovoked hate crime resulting in death, sexual assault against children, killing of more than one person in a single transaction of events, killing of law enforcement agents in the course of their duty, etc are all aggravating factors that open the criminal to capital felony. The law already exists. We don't need political gumbo's trying to make easy points and handicapping a functional system. <br>
<br>
It ain't broke, don't fix it until it is.<br>
<br>
