<br>
I agree that the crimes mentioned here are horrendous.  But shouldn't all horrendous crimes get the same punishment?  If I recall, the men convicted of the dragging death in Jasper got the death penalty.  If they already received the death penalty, then why is there a need to change the law?  They murdered an innocent man, and now they are paying the price.  They can't get a punishment that is anymore severe than what they are already getting.  Even if they dragged a white man to his death for no apparent reason, I think the punishment should still be the same.  Murder is illegal in this country, regardless of who or why you kill.  People who kill should be punished to the fullest extent of the law, period.  I have to agree with DB when he basically says that the only reason to add hate crimes on top of the conviction is to please certain interest groups.  If the killers are being executed, then there isn't anything more you can do.  <br>
<br>
I also want to make clear that I don't have a problem keeping record of motive when it comes to these crimes.  Although they can be subject to interpretation, it is good for us to see where people are coming from when they commit crimes so we can try to stop them at the source.  It is good to acknowledge when a hate crime is committed so we can educate the public about various groups in order to prevent further attacks.  I just don't agree with making hate crimes a charge in itself.  The act of violence says enough, and it should be punished accordingly.  <br>
